VSo, my journey began in the Bronx, New York,
p4
aVin a one-bedroom apartment,
p5
aVwith my two sisters and immigrant mother.
p6
aVI loved our neighborhood.
p7
aVIt was lively.
p8
aVThere was all this merengue blasting,
p9
aVneighbors socializing on building stoops
p10
aVand animated conversations over domino playing.
p11
aVIt was home,
p12
aVand it was sweet.
p13
aVBut it wasn't simple.
p14
aVIn fact, everyone at school knew the block where we lived,
p15
aVbecause it was where people came to buy weed and other drugs.
p16
aVAnd with drug-dealing comes conflict,
p17
aVso we often went to sleep to the sound of gunshots.
p18
aa(lp19
VI spent much of my childhood worried,
p20
aVworried about our safety.
p21
aVAnd so did our mother.
p22
aVShe worried that the violence we witnessed would overtake our lives;
p23
aVthat our poverty meant
p24
aVthat the neighbors with whom we lived and shared space
p25
aVwould harm us.
p26
aVOur entire life was in the Bronx,
p27
aVbut my mother's anxiety spurred her into action,
p28
aVand soon we were driving so fast to Connecticut \u2014
p29
aa(lp30
V(Laughter)
p31
aa(lp32
Vto boarding school campuses, with full scholarships in tow.
p33
aVMan, don't underestimate the power of a mother
p34
aVdetermined to keep her children safe.
p35
aa(lp36
V(Cheers)
p37
aV(Applause)
p38
aa(lp39
VAt boarding school,
p40
aVfor the first time,
p41
aVI was able to sleep without worry.
p42
aVI could leave my dorm room unlocked,
p43
aVwalk barefoot in the grass,
p44
aVand look up to see a night sky full of stars.
p45
aVHappy novelties.
p46
aa(lp47
VBut there were other novelties as well.
p48
aVVery quickly, I felt like I didn't belong.
p49
aVI learned that I didn't speak the right way,
p50
aVand to demonstrate the proper ways of speaking,
p51
aVmy teachers gave me frequent lessons, in public,
p52
aVon the appropriate way to enunciate certain words.
p53
aa(lp54
VA teacher once instructed me in the hallway:
p55
aV"Aaaaaas-king."
p56
aVShe said this loudly.
p57
aV"Dena, it's not 'axing,' like you're running around with an axe.
p58
aVThat's silly."
p59
aa(lp60
VNow at this point, you can imagine the snickers of my classmates,
p61
aVbut she continued:
p62
aV"Think about breaking the word into 'ass' and 'king,'
p63
aVand then put the two together to say it correctly \u2014
p64
aV'Asking.'"
p65
aa(lp66
VThere were some other moments that reminded me that I didn't belong.
p67
aVOnce, I walked into a classmate's dorm room,
p68
aVand I watched her watch her valuables around me.
p69
aVLike, why would she do that? I thought to myself.
p70
aVAnd then there was the time
p71
aVwhen another classmate walked into my dorm room,
p72
aVand yelled, "Ew!" as I was applying hair grease to my scalp.
p73
aa(lp74
VThere is emotional damage done when young people can't be themselves,
p75
aVwhen they are forced to edit who they are in order to be acceptable.
p76
aVIt's a kind of violence.
p77
